This paper deals with supervised learning in the presence of an adversary who can corrupt a limited number of features in each instance. This falls under the category of adversarial machine learning, which is typically classified under cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also discusses subspace voting techniques, which are commonly used in computer vision (cs.CV) and data mining (cs.DS). Additionally, the paper mentions the use of new datasets that deal with side channel electromagnetic information, which could fall under the categories of cryptography (cs.CR) or artificial intelligence (cs.AI) depending on the specific application.
